Chapter 5: Earth's Geomagnetism: Origin, Reversal, and Deflection

5.1 Observational Facts and Standard Model Difficulties
Earth possesses a stable dipole magnetic field, with the magnetic pole positions continuously drifting (the north magnetic pole currently migrating towards Siberia), and polarity reversals occurring every few hundred thousand to tens of millions of years, with extremely irregular intervals. The standard model's "iron-nickel dynamo" requires sustained convective drive, but the energy source for convection is unknown; reversals are attributed to "chaotic behavior," with no deterministic triggering mechanism.

5.2 TDMU Mechanism: Rotation-Shaped Macroscopically Ordered Fluid Equivalent to a Shared Link Network
Path I heat release drives fluid motion in the outer core, but pure thermal driving only produces random turbulence. Earth's rotation, as a global inertial mold, forcibly twists random thermal convection into large-scale toroidal vortices symmetric about the Earth's axis—this rotation-shaped macroscopically ordered motion is directly equivalent, in TDMU, to the large-scale directional alignment of shared links; this alignment closes end-to-end on the core scale, stably emerging as a dipole geomagnetic field. Polarity (N/S) corresponds to the overall chirality (left-handed or right-handed threading) of this giant fiber bundle. The stability stems from the fact that the direction of the core circulation is locked by Earth's rotation inertia; as long as Path I does not extinguish, this fiber bundle is continuously "refreshed" by the fluid.

No iron-nickel composition required: Jupiter's metallic hydrogen producing a magnetic field is ironclad proof—magnetic field essence is the equivalence of macroscopically ordered fluid to shared link alignment, independent of the fluid's specific composition.

5.3 Reversal: Global Chirality Phase Transition
Reversal corresponds to a large-scale chirality phase transition of the core circulation. When asymmetric accumulation of Path I heat output occurs between the northern and southern hemispheres (e.g., a temporary increase in the deep meshing rate in the northern hemisphere), it disrupts the axial symmetry of the original toroidal vortex. This asymmetric perturbation is amplified under rotation, forcing the entire circulation system to cross a topological bifurcation point—the chirality (handedness) of the fiber bundle flips. During this period, the dipole field decays into multipole isolated link loops (i.e., the disordered field of the reversal transition period).

The "anomalous" irregularity of reversal intervals: Localized Path II events (forced reconnection) inject reverse seed fiber bundles into the macroscopically ordered motion. If the intensity ratio of this seed fiber bundle to the old main fiber bundle exceeds a critical threshold, the system will trigger a global flip earlier or later than expected. This explains why reversal intervals are highly irregular, even exhibiting brief "flickering" reversals that quickly restore—that is when the reverse seed injected by Path II fails to conquer the main fiber bundle, merely temporarily distorting it.

5.4 Deflection: Meridional Precession of the Symmetry Axis
The symmetry axis of the dipole shared link network is not rigidly anchored to the crust. The macroscopically ordered motion of the outer core fluid exhibits a meridional velocity gradient (differential rotation of the fluid relative to the solid mantle). This differential motion drags the overall symmetry axis of the equivalent shared link bundle, causing slow meridional drift—this is the observed westward drift (about 0.2°/year). Simultaneously, the longitudinal non-uniformity of Path I reaction hot spots shifts the center of mass of the fluid circulation away from the geometric center, causing the surface projection points of the dipole axis ends to continuously migrate (the current north magnetic pole moving towards Siberia). Deflection is the continuous precession of the fluid symmetry axis, fundamentally distinct from reversal (chirality phase transition) in physical mechanism and timescale.

